@node Introduction "Introduction"

                                 @{b}@{fg shine}Introduction@{fg text}@{ub}

        LibSnooper is not a programme for average user. So, if you are
     not  a  programmer or you are not at home in Amiga OS then you do
     not need LibSnooper.

        It  is a bit difficult to say what is this programme for. As a
     matter of fact LibSnooper may be practicable in many applications
     -  it depends only on the user. Generally LibSnooper informs user
     about  calling functions from shared libraries. This fact is very
     usable   both  in debugging own programmes and in spying on other
     programmes.
@endnode

@node Setup "LibSnooper Setup Window"

                              @{b}@{fg shine}How to use Setup@{fg text}@{ub}

        After  you  run  LibSnooper you see it's window containing six
     gadgets.  Below,  there  is  description  of  each of them. After
     gadget  name  there  is  it's type in round brackets and keyboard
     shortcut in square brackets.

     @{fg fill}Libraries (listview)@{fg text}

        It  is not a list of libraries - this listview contains a list
     of  .fd  files  available.  Click on any position to have choosed
     file readed and displayed in next listview named:

     @{fg fill}Library functions (listview)@{fg text}

        Here  you  have  all  functions  descripted  in  .fd file from
     'Libraries' listview.

     @{fg fill}Choosed functions (listview)@{fg text}

        This  listview contains all functions you have choosed so far.
     Click  on one of them if yu want to remove it from list. You will
     have to confirm this operation.

     @{fg fill}Run LibSnooper (button)@{fg text} [@{fg shine}r@{fg text}]

        After  you  choosed  all  needed functions you can click here.
     Then Setup Window will be closed and LibSnooper will try to patch
     these functions. After successful patching at least one of them a
     main  task  of LibSnooper will be called. This task gets messages
     from installed patchcodes and prints them.

     @{fg fill}About (button)@{fg text} [@{fg shine}a@{fg text}]

        Information about LibSnooper and it's author.

     @{fg fill}Tasks to patch (string)@{fg text} [@{fg shine}t@{fg text}]

        Here  you  can  type  pattern of tasks you want to be patched.
     Default it is a '#?' which means that all tasks will be patched.

        And  there  are  rest  of  keyboard  shortuts,  which  are not
     ascribed to any gadget:

     [@{fg shine}Esc@{fg text}] lub [@{fg shine}q@{fg text}]

        Quit LibSnooper (you will have to confirm this operation).

     [@{fg shine}Tab@{fg text}]

        Changes  active  listviev.  It  is possible to change selected
     item using cursor keys only in active listview.

     [@{fg shine}CrsrUp@{fg text}]/[@{fg shine}CrsrDown@{fg text}]

        Use cursor keys to change selected item.

     [@{fg shine}Enter@{fg text}]

        Pressing  this  key  is analogous to click on selected item in
     active listviev (read listview gadgets description). 
@endnode

@node Running "LibSnooper Starting and Stopping"

                       @{b}@{fg shine}LibSnooper Starting and Stopping@{fg text}@{ub}

        LibSnooper  can  be  run  both from CLI and WorkBench. This is
     it's template:

     @{fg fill}LibSnooper FDPATH=FD/K,OUTPUT=OUT,CLOSEOUTPUT=CO/S@{fg text}

        Below,  there is description of each argument. Tooltypes names
     are the same as CLI arguments.

     @{fg fill}FDPATH=<path_to_fd_files>@{fg text}

        Directory, where you have your .fd files stored. Default it is
     FD: assign (there is no need to type this argument then).

     @{fg fill}OUTPUT=<output_file>@{fg text}

        A  file where the messages will be refered. This may be normal
     file,  CON:,  printer or something else. There is no need to type
     keyword OUTPUT when you run LibSnooper from CLI.

     @{fg fill}CLOSEOUTPUT@{fg text}

        Tells  LibSnooper  whether  to close output file after use. In
     case  when  output  is  a normal file this argument MUST be given
     else  you cannot read this file. But in case when output is a CLI
     window  you don't need to use this argument: LibSnooper may close
     this  window  before  you  manage  to  read  anything  (sometimes
     messages are printed very fast).

                   Stopping LibSnooper and Removing Patches

        To  stop  LibSnooper  and remove patches you must send to it a
     CTRL_C  signal.  It is possible to do it several ways. When a CLI
     window  is  set as OUTPUT just activate it and press [Ctrl+C]. In
     other case you may use system monitor (e.g. ARTM or Scout) or run
     little programme named LibSnooper_STOP included in archive. After
     LibSnooper  gets  signal CTRL_C it will attempt to remove patches
     (a CLI window with message "Attempting to remove patches..." will
     be  opened).  Note  that  it is not always possible to remove all
     patches.  You  can  try  again  then  but  be prepared that (very
     seldom) it will not be possible at all. 
@endnode

@node Work  "How does it work?

                          @{b}@{fg shine}How does LibSnooper work?@{fg text}@{ub}

        After you pressed "Run LibSnooper" button some messages should
     be printed. Of course it depends what function(s) are patched and
     what  pattern  is  set in string gadget. To cut long story short:
     there  must  be  some tasks matching this pattern calling choosed
     functions.  It is good for a start to set CLI window as an OUTPUT
     and take a look at the messages. Example message looks like that:
@{b}
dos.library/Open(name,accessMode)(d1/d2)
Data: ffffffff 78273800 000003ed 00000100 00000000 00000000 00000000 00000001
Addr: 78273800 78273813 00000000 78033d18 78177e68 7827391c 78011c7c --------
Task: dopus_lister
Result:   782446b8
@{ub}
        First  line  containing  ofcourse  library and function names.
     Next  there  is  contetns  of  data registers (D0-D7) and address
     registers  (A0-A6).  Then  we have name of task which called that
     function and result (value that function returned in D0 register)

        Together with LibSnooper any memory monitor may be very usable
     (ofcourse it depends on functions you would like to patch). Let's
     take  look  at  the  example  above.  Open()  function  needs two
     arguments:  'name'  in  D1 and 'accessMode' in D2. In D1 there is
     $78273800.  Just run a memory monitor - at this address should be
     name  of  just  opeded  file. Value $000003ed is a MODE_OLDFILE -
     file  was opened for read operation. Result value is non-zero. It
     means that opening file succeed.
@endnode

@node Requirements "System requirements"

                                 @{b}@{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}
     - An Amiga with OS 3.0+
     - patch.library V5+
     - a set of .fd files
@endnode

@node Errors "Error messages"

                                @{b}@{fg shine}Error Messages@{fg text}@{ub}

        Below are descripted some error messages might be displayed by
     LibSnooper.

     @{fg fill}@{i}"LibSnooper error:
      Could not open <library> version <version_number>.
      Press Enter to close window..."@{fg text}@{ui}

        LibSnooper   could  not  find  library  in  required  version.
     Probably  there  is  no  patch.library.  Newest  version  of this
     library can be found on Aminet in util/libs.

     @{fg fill}@{i}"No .fd files found..."@{fg text}@{ui}

        There  is  no .fd files in given directory or such a directory
     does not exists. You should change tooltype named FDPATH (or type
     FD=<your_path> when running programme from CLI) to proper path.

     @{fg fill}@{i}"It was NOT possible to install patch on function
      <function_name>"@{fg text}@{ui}
      or
     @{fg fill}@{i}"It was NOT possible to install after-patch on function
      <function_name>"@{fg text}@{ui}

        LibSnooper  could not patch function <function_name>. There is
     a  few  possibilities  of  this error but most probably it is not
     function  from a shared library. The .fd files describes not only
     libraries  but  also  other  system  elements  (e.g.  files  like
     cia_lib.fd  or  potgo_lib.fd).  Since  LibSnooper  can only patch
     functions  from libraries this will cause an error. First message
     informs  that  LibSnooper  could not install patch at all. Second
     one  informs that it was not possible to install only second part
     of  the  patch.  Each  function  is  patched twice: first code is
     executed  before  original  function  and  the  second  one after
     original function returns. 
@endnode

@node Instalation "Instalation"

                                 @{b}@{fg shine}Instalation@{fg text}@{ub}

        The  sipliest  way  to  install  LibSnooper is to use included
     Install  script.  Anyway,  if  you want to do it manually keep on
     reading.  First  copy files LibSnooper and LibSnooper_STOP to any
     directory (you can also copy this guide if you want to). Then you
     should  inform  LibSnooper  where are your .fd files stored. Just
     edit  tooltype  named  FDPATH  in  LibSnooper's  icon  (it is not
     necessary  if  there is a FD: assign in your system). And finally
     copy  patch.library  to LIBS:. Now you have LibSnooper installed.
@endnode

@node Future "What's in future"

                              @{b}@{fg shine}What's in future?@{fg text}@{ub}

        LibSnooper's  future  depends  on it's users. If there are any
     errors  detected  (I'm sure they are ;) or anybody tells me about
     some interesting ideas I will write new version.
@endnode

